<h2>Choosing the Right Varieties</h2>
<p>
  In short growing seasons, variety selection directly affects success.
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Early or short-season varieties (55–70 days)</strong> mature more reliably before fall frost.</li>
  <li><strong>Determinate types</strong> concentrate production into a shorter window.</li>
  <li><strong>Smaller fruit types</strong> (cherry, saladette) ripen faster than large slicers.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Large beefsteak varieties often require sustained nighttime temperatures above
  55°F (13°C) to fully mature. In climates with cool nights, fruit may stall before ripening.
</p>

<p>
  For a full breakdown of how temperature affects tomato growth, see
  <a href="/guides/is-45-degrees-too-cold-for-tomato-plants/">Is 45 Degrees Too Cold for Tomato Plants?</a>.
</p>
</section>

<section class="card">
<h2>Temperature Limits That Affect Maturity</h2>

<p>
  Even after frost risk declines, temperature stability determines how quickly tomatoes finish.
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Above 60°F (16°C):</strong> Strong, steady growth</li>
  <li><strong>50–59°F (10–15°C):</strong> Slower development</li>
  <li><strong>45°F (7°C):</strong> Noticeable slowdown</li>
  <li><strong>Below 40°F (4°C):</strong> Stress likely</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Repeated cool nights delay flowering and fruit ripening, even if plants survive.
</p>

<p>
  For a full overview of seedling cold tolerance thresholds (45°, 40°, 35°, 32°),
  see <a href="/guides/cold-tolerance-of-seedlings/">Cold Tolerance of Seedlings: Temperature Survival Guide</a>.
</p>
</section>

<section class="card">
<h2>Common Short-Season Mistakes</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Starting too late indoors.</strong> This compresses harvest time.</li>
  <li><strong>Transplanting into cold soil.</strong> Roots stall below 60°F (16°C).</li>
  <li><strong>Ignoring nighttime temperatures.</strong> Repeated lows below 50°F (10°C) delay fruit set.</li>
  <li><strong>Ignoring fall frost planning.</strong> Fruit needs time to ripen before the first hard freeze.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  In colder regions across northern U.S. states and comparable Canadian climates,
  even a one-week delay can reduce total yield.
</p>

<p>
  To plan your fall cutoff date, use the
  <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost &amp; Fall Planting Planner</a>.
</p>
</section>

<section class="card">
<h2>Can Tomatoes Finish Before Frost?</h2>

<p>
  Count backward from your average first fall frost date using your variety’s
  days to maturity.
</p>

<p>
  For example:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>First frost: September 25</li>
  <li>Variety maturity: 65 days</li>
  <li>Latest transplant target: Late July</li>
</ul>

<p>
  If remaining warm days are limited, consider:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Using row covers during early fall cold snaps</li>
  <li>Pruning excess foliage mid-season</li>
  <li>Removing late flowers 4–6 weeks before frost</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Reliable maturity depends on both calendar days <em>and</em> temperature consistency.
</p>
</section>

